ce:section.ce:para:
A series of CDs, both pristine and heteroatom-doped, were synthesized via a facile one-pot thermolysis method based on previously reported procedures [4,6,27]. The synthetic pathways are schematically illustrated in Fig. 1
                        , with detailed information on reagents provided in the Supporting Information. Citric acid was used as the primary and only precursor for the synthesis of undoped CDs Citric acid was used as the primary and only precursor for the synthesis of undoped CDs, as it is widely reported due to its high availability and the ease of preparing materials with notable luminescent properties [24,27,40]. For the preparation of N- and S-doped samples, secondary precursors were added at specific molar ratios (Table 1
                        ), selected based on their successful use in previous studies [41–45]. In a typical synthesis, the precursors were combined in a glass vial reactor without any solvent addition. The vial was then heated to 230 °C for 2 h on a temperature-controlled heating block equipped with a magnetic stirrer operating at 100 rpm. Following the reaction, the products were allowed to cool to ambient temperature before CD purification.
